Fighting Churn at Model Fitness Gym¶

In this project we will analyze gym customer profiles and come up with a customer retention strategy. We will predict the probability of churn for the upcoming month for each customer. We willd raw up typical user portraits: select the most outstanding groups and describe their main features. We will analyze the factors that impact churn most, describe patterns with respect to interaction with customers and the draw basic conclusions and develop recommendations on how to improve customer service for different target groups. We will suggest measures to cut churn and increase retention.

Table of Contents:¶

Step 2. Carring out exploratory data analysis (EDA)

The majority of the columns actually represent bool values - gender, proximity to home/work, being partner company member, bringing a friend, giving phone, visiting group classes and churn. Let's analyze there mean values:
Gender - half of the clients are male, half - female.
Near Location - the majority of the clients live/work close to the gym.
Partner - half of the clients belong to the partner company, half not.
Promo friends - only 1/3 bring a friend.
Phone - the majority of the users provide a phone number.
Group visits - less than a half of the clients go to the group classes.
Churn - less of the 1/3 of the clients leave.

The non-bool columns are: contract period, age, additional charges, number of months till the end of the contract, lifetime value, frequency of visiting classes in general and last month in particular.
Contract period - the mean values stands on more than 4 months, with pretty big std. The majority of the clients sign for 6th months.
Age - the mean age of the clients is 29 years old, th emajority of the clients are a bit older than 30.
Additional charges - in avarage people spend around 150 USD, the majority not more than 210 USD.
Months till the end of the contract - the values are pretty similar to the contract period values, meaning that there are a lot of new clients who just start in the gym.
Lifetime - in avarage clients last for almost 4 months, the majority around 5 months. Meaning that if people buy 6 months, they use them almost fully.
Frequency of the classes visits per week - almost 2 in avarage and a bit less per week last month.

Look at the mean feature values in two groups: for those who left (churn) and for those who stayed (use the groupby() method).

# Calculating grid parameters
num_cols = 3
charts_count = len(data_distributions.columns) - 1
num_rows = math.ceil(float(charts_count)/num_cols)

# Layout and style
single_chart_width = 7
single_chart_height = 5

fig, axes =plt.subplots(ncols=num_cols, nrows=num_rows, squeeze=False)
fig.set_size_inches(num_cols * single_chart_width, num_rows * single_chart_height)

plt.suptitle('Features Distribution',size=16)
labels = ["Stayed", "Left"]
bar_plots = ['Gender', 'Near Location', 'Partner', 'Promo Friends', 'Phone', 'Group Visits']

#Plotting
for index, col in enumerate(data_distributions.drop('Churn', axis = 1).columns):
    ax = axes[int(index / num_cols)][index % num_cols]
    if col in bar_plots:
        plot = sns.countplot(data = data_distributions, hue="Churn", x=col, ax=ax, palette="vlag")
        plot.legend_.remove()
    else:
        sns.kdeplot(data = data_distributions, hue="Churn", x=col, ax=ax, legend=False, palette="vlag", fill=True)

fig.legend(data_distributions['Churn'],    
           labels=labels,   
           loc="center right",  
           borderaxespad=0.1,    
           title=" ")

# Droppping empty cells
cells_in_last_row = charts_count % num_cols
if(cells_in_last_row > 0):
    last_row = axes[len(axes) - 1]
    for i in range(cells_in_last_row, len(last_row)):
        fig.delaxes(last_row[i])
plt.show()

Step 3. Building a model to predict user churn ¶

Build a binary classification model for customers where the target feature is the user's leaving next month.¶

Divide the data into train and validation sets using the train_test_split() function.

In [11]:
#Spliting the data
X = data.drop('Churn', axis = 1)
y = data['Churn']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_st = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_st = scaler.transform(X_test)

Train the model on the train set with two methods: logistic regression, random forest.

# Using the trained model to make predictions
rf_predictions = rf_model.predict(X_test_st) # write your code here
rf_probabilities = rf_model.predict_proba(X_test_st)[:,1]

Evaluate accuracy, precision, and recall for both models using the validation data. Use them to compare the models. Which model gave better results?

In [15]:
#Creating a function to evaluate metrics of the models
def print_all_metrics(y_true, y_pred, y_proba, title = 'Classification metrics'):
    print(title)
    print('\tAccuracy: {:.2f}'.format(accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)))
    print('\tPrecision: {:.2f}'.format(precision_score(y_true, y_pred)))
    print('\tRecall: {:.2f}'.format(recall_score(y_true, y_pred)))
In [16]:

Step 5. Conclusions and basic recommendations on working with customers ¶

We have studied and prepared the dataset of 4000 entries about the gym clients characteristics for the analysis and churn prediction.
We have studied features distribution and correlation between them. For feature interdependence we can mark:
Contract period and months till the end of the contract, frequency of visiting classes per week in general and last month. From the correlation matrix heatmap the target variable "Churn" didn't have one leading influencing feature.
We split the data into validaion and test sets and chose Logistic Regressor as the prediction model, basing on the higher performance metrics.
We built an hierarchical clustering dendrogram and saw 4 user clusters, but for the sake of the task given we used K-mean algorithm with 5 clusters. We studied the distribution of features in each cluster and found out that each cluster has its main outstanding feature.
As for the churn we saw 2 clusters with the highest churn rate.

Recomendations:

We've noticed that clients who choose to leave in average less belong to the partner companies, bring less friends, sign for shorter time the contract, are younger, visit less classes, spend less money on additional products. We would recomend to promote these strategy:

  1. Sign with more companies - corporate clients are more stable, may be they go in groups with the collegues and it becomes their tradition.
  2. Add more bonuses for the clients bringing a friend to sign with the gym, it can be a good motivation.
  3. Promote longterm contracts - introduce some attractive discounts.
  4. Make it attractive to visit classes and spend more on additional products, it seems that the more a client is involved in the activities, the more attached he becomes.
